<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Lebanon     09-03 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Lebanon,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Bombs Guerrilla Base in South Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> warplanes destroyed a guerrilla base in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> 21 miles north of the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> border Monday, the army said. All planes returned safely from the early morning raid, a military statement said. An army spokesman said the planes struck a guerrilla base in the village of <LOCATION> Majdal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Balhis </LOCATION>, about three miles east of <LOCATION> Mashghara </LOCATION>. The spokesman, who is not identified under military regulations, would not say which militia operated the base nor give the reason for the raid. The air raid follows attacks Wednesday and Thursday in which Katyusha rockets were fired at <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Galilee </LOCATION> district from south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The attacks caused no injuries, but one rocket damaged a house in <LOCATION> Kiryat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shmona </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Galilee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Panhandle </LOCATION>. Israeli authorities blamed that rocket attack on the militant Shiite Moslem militia <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God. Also on Thursday, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops fought a battle with four guerrillas just north of the border, and one member of the Shiite militia Amal was killed. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> suffered no casualties in the firefight. The air attack was the the 10th time Israeli war planes have struck in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> this year. The last raid, on Aug. 27, was aimed at a <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> base.
</TEXT>
