<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Godoy,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experienced Politician Chosen As Opposition Running Mate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reyes </PERSON> brings solid political experience and a controversial personality to the campaign for which he is running as opposition vice presidential candidate in next February's election. While crowds at the headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opposition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> on Saturday night cheered <PERSON> Violeta </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrios </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>, the presidential candidate, hecklers three times shouted the name of <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON>'s rival for the No. 2 spot. While perhaps not an auspicious start for a political candidate, <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON>'s strong personality _ which some have described as arrogant and abrasive _ can take the heckling. The hostility stems from his four-year, eight-month tenure as Labor Minister under the leftist Sandinista government, against which he is running now. As Labor Minister, <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON> instituted a system of salary levels that became widely unpopular. Detractors say his government post also makes his allegiance to the opposition somewhat suspect. <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON> was Labor Minister from July 19, 1979 to March 31, 1984, when he resigned. He said later that he quit because he disagreed with the leftist Sandinista ideology. His resignation however reflects his political talent _ the government gave him a going-away reception, showing he must have left in good stead. The 55-year-old lawyer has been better at defending himself from power plays within his own party, the Independent Liberals, than in attacking the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. Political attacks against <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON> stem not only from his personality as from his tenure as president of the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> for 10 years. One critic, who prefered to remain unidentified, called <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON> `` dictatorial and Machiavellian.'' <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON> follows a long tradition of Liberalism in his family. His grandfather, Gen. <PERSON> Paulino </PERSON> <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON>, was the spearhead of the <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Liberal revolution of 1983. He has said that the slogan of the French revolution, `` Liberty, Equality, Brotherhood,'' encapsules the most important concepts for the individual and society. <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON> is married to <PERSON> Sonia </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercado </PERSON>, a Mexican; they have three children.
</TEXT>
