<HEAD>Two People Shot, Over 100 Stores Looted in Va Beach Rioting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE with resort strip closed, add
quotes, other detail. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rioting broke out early Sunday in this resort city, and more than 100 downtown stores were looted and at least two people shot before a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> military police attachment was deployed, authorities said. <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON>, assistant director of public information for <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, said guardsmen were called out by Gov. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON> shortly after 4 a.m. to assist local authorities. She did not have exact figures on the number of guardsmen involved. She said the rioting began around 2 a.m. when police confronted a mob on <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION>, the main beachfront thoroughfare. She had no estimate on the crowd size or what may have set off the rioting. City Manager <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> ordered much of the resort strip closed, and residents were told to avoid the area. An estimated more than 25,000 college students from predominantly black schools up and down the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> are in town for the annual Greekfest. <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> said she did n't know if the riot was related to the gathering. Police reported at least four injuries, including the two men shot. <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> was unable to identify any of the injured or say what their condition was. She said police officers were not involved in the shootings. Police reported scattered gunfire and several fires in the area overnight. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said police, backed by state troopers and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, were in `` crowd control positions'' in the oceanfront area. At 7 a.m., the area was reported quiet. <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanz </PERSON>, front desk manager at the <LOCATION> Kona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Motel </LOCATION>, said authorities were not allowing anyone to leave the hotel `` even for breakfast'' unless they were checking out to go home. Many college students were staying at the motel, and they remained in their rooms while guardsmen and police patrolled the streets, she said. `` It's a heck of a way to end the season,'' she said. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bremer </PERSON>, desk clerk at the <LOCATION> Kona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> two blocks away, said some families were checking out of the motel early. He said cash registers from nearby stores had been hurled into the street by looters. `` It's pretty messy,'' he said.
