<HEAD>Vietnamese Leader Stands Firm Against Democratic Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vietnamese leader <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Linh </PERSON> sharply rejected a multi-party system for his Communist nation and declared that freedom of speech amounts to anarchy. Expressing unease with the kind of changes sweeping the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, and other Communist countries, <PERSON> Linh </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> would keep liberalizing its economy but not its political system. `` It is not our policy to hasten renovation of the political system while preparations are still inadequate,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader said. `` Neither is it our intention to effect limitless democratization.'' `` The Communist Party of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> is the leader, initiator and pacesetter in renovation,'' <PERSON> Linh </PERSON> said. `` We shall not allow any force to set up any opposition party to work against the people and against socialism. Once again, we declare that we resolutely reject pluralism, a multi-party system or opposition parties.'' His comments came in a 10,000-word speech laden with Marxist terminology and dogma. <PERSON> Linh </PERSON>, an economic reformer who has also taken some steps toward political liberalization, gave the address at a meeting in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> on Friday to mark <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s National Day. A text was seen in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> on Sunday. Its basic thrust reflected a recent conservative trend in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>, with official media lashing out at liberal reform in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Some observers believe the trend stems from leaders' fears that <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s `` open-door'' economic policy will lead to a popular pro-democracy movement such as occurred in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Others, however, believe the rece