<HEAD>Texas Towns Feud Over Super Collider Fame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAXAHACHIE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The superconducting super collider project has got three towns on a super collision course over bragging rights to the giant atom smasher, bringing out their big artillery on billboards and bumper stickers. All three _ <LOCATION> Waxahachie </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ennis </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Midlothian </LOCATION> _ want people to think of their town first when they think of the collider which is slated for <LOCATION> Ellis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and, in fact, wo n't touch any of the three. The fight is n't quite so heated as the battle that preceded it, when politicians all over the country sought to get the multibillion-dollar federal project in their state. Instead, it's a battle fought with bumper stickers and billboards. <PERSON> Ennis </PERSON> proclaims itself `` Super Collider Country'' and <LOCATION> Midlothian </LOCATION> boasts it's the `` Gateway to the Super Collider.'' So far, <LOCATION> Waxahachie </LOCATION> has smashed the competition. At 18,150 people, it is the biggest town in <LOCATION> Ellis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and will be encircled by the 53-mile collider ring. It calls itself `` The Center of Attention, Home of the super collider.'' The other two towns are on the outskirts of the ring, which is to be built in the country south of <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>. Shortly after the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced in November that <LOCATION> Ellis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> would be the collider site, the <ORGANIZATION> Waxahachie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> printed hundreds of bumper stickers proclaiming itself the center. The town also rented billboard space off Interstate 35 to carry the same message. That was enough to make officials in <LOCATION> Ennis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Midlothian </LOCATION> stomp in protest. <PERSON> Ennis </PERSON>, a town of about 14,150 people east of <LOCATION> Waxahachie </LOCATION>, countered with its own boast on a billboard on Interstate 45. `` The only thing <LOCATION> Waxahachie </LOCATION> has is its name,'' said <PERSON> Kipp </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Ennis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. `` It sticks. Even though it's hard to say, you do n't forget it.'' <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Sokoll </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Waxahachie </LOCATION> city manager, scoffs at such talk. `` We are not going to let one peon city to the east like <LOCATION> Ennis </LOCATION> think they are the home of the super collider,'' <PERSON> Sokoll </PERSON> said. `` The only thing <PERSON> Ennis </PERSON> does better than us is play football.'' <LOCATION> Midlothian </LOCATION>, population 5,000, wo n't be left out, said <PERSON> Pam </PERSON> <PERSON> Mundo </PERSON>, executive director of the town's chamber of commerce. She's the one who came up with the slogan: `` We are the Gateway to the Super Collider.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the state agency in charge of acquiring the land for the collider, is shying away from the feud. `` We have tried not to get caught up in the local competition,'' commission spokeswoman <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> said last week. `` We have always referred to the super collider as being in <LOCATION> Ellis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>.'' Ground has not been broken for the colossal project, but officials say it should be operational by 1996. The collider is expected to reveal new information about the nature of matter and the origins of the universe. It will hurl minute beams of protons toward one another inside a 53-mile tunnel. It is expected to create 4,000 temporary construction jobs and 3,000 permanent positions.
