 <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> promised that the party will not use force to hold onto power if it loses the nation's first multi-party elections next year, a newspaper reported Sunday. In an interview by the daily <ORGANIZATION> Helsingin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sanomat </ORGANIZATION> newspaper, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> acknowledged that Hungarian communists want to wield power. However, he added that the party would `` draw its own conclusions'' if it were to lose the elections, due to be held at the latest in 1990, according to the paper. `` We would not be satisfied with such a situation,'' <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> was quoted as saying. However, he ruled out using force as a political weapon, saying, `` We would not use tanks but political arguments to get back into power.'' He said he will step down as party general secretary during a party congress on Oct. 6, but that he would continue to be active in politics. `` I want to remain in the party leadership,'' he said. In <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> was scheduled to meet with President <PERSON> Mauno </PERSON> <PERSON> Koivisto </PERSON> on Monday. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>'s power was diluted in June when party reformers established a ruling presidium with the general secretary as one of four members. Party chairman <PERSON> Rezsoe </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyers </PERSON> has described himself as `` first among equals'' on the new body. In <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> on Sunday, the reformers preparing for the party congress clashed over how far to go in revamping the party. Presidium members <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON>, <PERSON> Miklos </PERSON> <PERSON> Nemeth </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Nyers </PERSON> spoke at a two-day conference of reformist communists held to plan strategy for the October congress. <PERSON> Nyer