<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A majority of Britons blame bad management, rather than labor unions, for the nation's economic woes, a public opinion survey reported. The Sunday Times, which commissioned the poll, said 60 percent of respondents believe management is more to blame than unions. When asked if unions have too much power, 42 percent said no and 41 percent said yes _ the first time since 1975 that more respondents took the unions' side on that question in the poll, the report said. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> had a Labor government in 1975. It was ousted in 1979 after a winter of strikes against a pay freeze. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s Conservatives are still in power 10 years later after restricting union power to call strikes and to support them with sympathy actions. A majority said most unions are controlled by a few extremists and militants, but 77 percent said unions are needed to protect workers' interests. The polling company, <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, said it questioned 1,946 adults, including 440 union members, across the country. No margin of error was reported. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has low economic investment which results in steadily falling manufacturing capacity, low economic growth, unemployment ranging up to 25 percent in the older industrial areas, and a declining share of world markets.
