 Here at a glance is President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s emergency aid package to <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> to help that government fight its war against powerful cocaine cartels __ COST: $ 65 million. __ EQUIPMENT: Two C-130B transport planes, five UH-1H transport helicopters, eight A-37 reconnaissance and attack jets, and an unspecified number of trucks, small boats, radios, grenade launchers, machine guns, rifles, pistols, and other equipment. Also bulletproof vests for Colombian judges and other officials who attempt to prosecute suspected drug traffickers. __ <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. PERSONNEL _ Up to 200, although not necessarily all at the same time, according to the Pentagon. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> has expressed wariness about the presence of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops on its soil, and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials have been evasive in providing specific numbers. __ DELIVERY _ The C-130s arrived Sunday, carrying some of the smaller items in the package. The A-37s were due Monday, and the helicopters on Tuesday. No specific schedule was announced for completing the delivery.
