<HEAD>Saving Lives Is Getting To Be a Habit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A utility company employee says saving lives seems to be a fringe benefit of his job. In the past three years, <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> has helped rescued a family from a burning home, revived a girl suffering from a seizure and resuscitated a man who got a 12,000-volt shock. `` It just seems natural,'' <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> said. `` You know what has to be done, and you go in and do it.'' <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON>, a troubleshooter for the <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, was called to investigate a power failure in July in an electrical substation in <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>. He arrived 12 minutes later to find a man who seemed to be dead. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Albright </PERSON> had gotten past a barbed-wire fence and warning signs into the substation, where he was badly burned by a 12,000-volt transformer. He was hospitalized for some time, but is now out and attending physical therapy. `` He was pretty much lifeless,'' <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> said. `` He was n't breathing, and if he had a pulse, I sure could n't find it. <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> administered cardio-pulmonary resuscitation, called rescue workers and helped them make their way around dangerous electrical equipment before fixing the power outage. `` I'm proud, and I'm glad I was the one who responded to the call,'' said <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON>, who teaches life-saving techniques at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>. Three years ago, <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> and two co-workers received citations from KG & amp; E for their rescue of a Valley Center family. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> gave <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> its highest award for resuscitating 2-year-old <PERSON> Regina </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> after she underwent a seizure. <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> said he loves his job because it allows him to work outdoors and meet people. Saving the occasional life, he said, is just a fringe benefit.
