<TEXT>
 A car full of teen-agers who may have been fleeing a party raided by police missed a stone bridge and plunged into a shallow creek, killing six students from a rural high school, authorities said Sunday. The five boys and one girl, all believed to be between 15 and 17, may have been dead for up to 20 hours before the car was found, police said. The car went off a gravel road, missed the bridge and went down a ravine, landing in the creek partially submerged on its side. The accident was discovered by a boy walking along the road about 6 p.m. Saturday, but authorities said they were checking reports of a loud crash as early as 10 p.m. Friday. `` There's a chance they were there for some time,'' <LOCATION> Brown </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff's Capt. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> said. `` Where they ended up, the car was n't visible from the road.'' The victims' identities were being withheld Sunday. School Superintendent <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lark </PERSON> confirmed all they were all students at <ORGANIZATION> Wrightstown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION> is an incorporated town within <LOCATION> Wrightstown </LOCATION>, a rural community of 1,020 residents about 15 miles south of <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. Principal <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> called the victims `` typical teen-age kids for this area'' and said he did not know where the victims had been or were going before the accident. But a group of teen-agers gathered outside <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Wrightstown </LOCATION> on Sunday morning said they had known the victims from school and heard they had left a party that police raided. `` They all to