 <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Caren </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON> were a romantic young couple when they sank their life savings into a homemade fiberglass sailboat for a voyage around the world. More than eight years later _ or 55 countries, 58,000 miles, and two children later _ the Suttons sailed under the Golden Gate to return home on Saturday. `` To be honest, it's a lot of work _ and a lot of fun,'' <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON> said. `` Anybody can do it. Just go for it.'' The couple and their two daughters born during the family's odyssey were welcomed at the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yacht </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> by dozens of family and friends and a proclamation of welcome from the city The Suttons, sailing novices who first shared the dream of traveling around the world while high school sweethearts, started building their 43-foot sailing yawl, the <LOCATION> Marinka </LOCATION>, 14 years ago. The couple sold their possessions and sailed out beyond the Golden Gate in March 1981. Three days before their scheduled departure, <PERSON> Caren </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON> learned she was pregnant. `` She was very nervous about that. They had to reconsider the trip. They thought about it for a long time and decided to go,'' said her mother, <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Caren </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON>, after a first leg of the voyage that gave new meaning to the term morning sickness, gave birth to <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>, now 7, in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON>, now 5, was born in <LOCATION> Pago </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pago </LOCATION>. `` It was my husband's dream and I just went along with it,'' <PERSON> Caren </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON> said. `` He did everything, from navigating to operating the radio. ... I take orders very well, cook and take