<HEAD>Government Doesn't Want Human Rights Groups In Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> said Sunday he would not allow international human rights groups into <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> to investigate alleged rights abuses. Also Sunday, an Information Department statement said 24 people were killed over the weekend by Sinhalese radicals from the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, an ultranationalist guerrilla group seeking to overthrow the government The victims included five women relatives of security force personnel, 12 civilians, five soldiers, a doctor and a postal official, the statement said. It gave no further details. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>'s declaration regarding human rights came after he met with a six-member opposition group called the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliamentarians </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opposition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fundamental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>. The group urged the president to safeguard human rights, the statement said. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> said the government was not prepared to permit international human rights groups, including <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, to visit the country. He told opposition leaders that `` human rights is not the preserve of one party or group,'' according to the statement. Opposition politicians and human rights groups have accused the military and pro-government vigilante groups of killing hundreds of civilians suspected of sympathizing with Sinhalese radicals. At least 1,222 people have been killed since June 20, when <PERSON>