<FIRST>r w AM-DrugKillings 1stLd-Writethru a0658 09-03 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Killings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Number of Police Killed in Action Sets Record in 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: To CLARIFY rate of police deaths per drug 100,000 drug arrests
in 1976 and 1980, SUBS 7th graf pvs: The previous ....; picks up 8th graf:
While the ....^ ^By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drug-related killings of police officers hit a record high in 1988, but the rate of officer deaths to narcotics enforcement remains surprisingly low, a private study concludes. According to the study issued Sunday by the Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> Crime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, 14 officers were killed in drug enforcement activities such as raids, arrests and serving warrants, including one who was assassinated in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. By contrast, killings of police officers have averaged seven a year since 1972, when the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> began publishing narratives on how police officers died in the line of duty. By another measure, the proportion of all police murders attributable to drugs has risen from 6 percent in 1985 to 18 percent in 1988, the report said. <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> Professor <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON>, who also heads the institute, said part of the reason for the increase is the increased drug enforcement activity. Estimated drug arrests have set a record each year since reaching 708,000 in 1984, rising to 1.1 million in 1988, <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> said. The numbers of police murders per drug arrest rose from .71 to 100,000 in 1984 to 1.22 per 100,000 in 1988. The all-time record rate of drug arrest-related police killings was in 1976, when 1.96 officers died per 100,000 arrests, followed by 1980 when there were 1.89 police killings for every 100,000 drug arrests. `` While the risk of death per arrest is still not as high as in the record years of 1976 and 1980, this trend is still an ominous one,'' the study said. `` The record levels of drug enforcement, combined with rising risk levels per arrest, suggest that the total murders of police in drug enforcement will increase in future years.'' Putting the risk in perspective, the report noted that officers who make two drug arrests a day, 220 days a year, for 25 years will make only 5,500 drug arrests. `` Career drug arrests may total, on average, less than 100 for the typical officer,'' it said. `` At these levels of drug enforcement activity, odds of one death per 100,000 drug arrests are pretty safe bets.'' Of the killings since 1972, 33 percent happened during undercover `` buy and bust'' operations, 32 percent while serving warrants or conducting raids, and 5 percent were `` ambushed'' during surveillance or killed to prevent their testimony. Referring to the ambush killings, the report said: `` These cases are a mere handful compared to the 220 judges and other court officials slain in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, apparently by drug dealers, since 1981. But it is striking that four out of six of these <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cases occurred in the period from 1985 through 1988.'' The study did not count killings outside drug enforcement even if the killer was under the influence of drugs, was a known or past drug dealer or in possession of drugs. Additionally, the report did not mention non-fatal injuries to officers.
</TEXT>
