<HEAD>Gunman Loots BayBank Machines of Nearly $150,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUXBURY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A gunman disabled an automatic bank machine, waited for repair workers to arrive, held them up and made off with $ 150,000 from the machine, police said Sunday. Police are still searching for the robber, who forced two <ORGANIZATION> BayBank </ORGANIZATION> workers to open the back of a money machine, then looted it of cash. `` He tied them up and cleaned out the machine,'' said Police Lt. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Sjostedt </PERSON>. Investigators are studying photo tapes taken during transactions before Saturday's robbery, he said. <PERSON> Sjostedt </PERSON> said police believe the money machine was broken intentionally by the thief in order to bring repair workers. A faulty machine activates a signal in the bank's central system. The employees were returning to their car around midnight when the gunman wearing a stocking mask and gloves pointed a revolver at them and herded them back to the machine in a shopping plaza. The thief escaped in a car belonging to one of the bank workers, but it was found abandoned on Route 3. After freeing themselves, the bank workers set off an alarm in the bank machine, bringing police to the scene about 10 minutes after the robbery. A spokesman for the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> office of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said the method used in the theft was unusual. `` There have been robberies at teller machines,'' he said, `` but I do n't think anything like this has every happened. It was pretty significant.''
